print(digits.DESCR)  # to get the descriptive information about this dataset

Optical Recognition of Handwritten Digits Data Set
===================================================

Notes
-----
Data Set Characteristics:
    :Number of Instances: 5620
    :Number of Attributes: 64
    :Attribute Information: 8x8 image of integer pixels in the range 0..16.
    :Missing Attribute Values: None
    :Creator: E. Alpaydin (alpaydin '@' boun.edu.tr)
    :Date: July; 1998

This is a copy of the test set of the UCI ML hand-written digits datasets
http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Optical+Recognition+of+Handwritten+Digits

The data set contains images of hand-written digits: 10 classes where
each class refers to a digit.

Preprocessing programs made available by NIST were used to extract
normalized bitmaps of handwritten digits from a preprinted form. From a
total of 43 people, 30 contributed to the training set and different 13
to the test set. 32x32 bitmaps are divided into nonoverlapping blocks of
4x4 and the number of on pixels are counted in each block. This generates
an input matrix of 8x8 where each element is an integer in the range
0..16. This reduces dimensionality and gives invariance to small
distortions.

For info on NIST preprocessing routines, see M. D. Garris, J. L. Blue, G.
T. Candela, D. L. Dimmick, J. Geist, P. J. Grother, S. A. Janet, and C.
L. Wilson, NIST Form-Based Handprint Recognition System, NISTIR 5469,
1994.

References
----------
  - C. Kaynak (1995) Methods of Combining Multiple Classifiers and Their
    Applications to Handwritten Digit Recognition, MSc Thesis, Institute of
    Graduate Studies in Science and Engineering, Bogazici University.
  - E. Alpaydin, C. Kaynak (1998) Cascading Classifiers, Kybernetika.
  - Ken Tang and Ponnuthurai N. Suganthan and Xi Yao and A. Kai Qin.
    Linear dimensionalityreduction using relevance weighted LDA. School of
    Electrical and Electronic Engineering Nanyang Technological University.
    2005.
  - Claudio Gentile. A New Approximate Maximal Margin Classification
    Algorithm. NIPS. 2000.

y = digits.target
X = digits.data
a = int(100*random.random())
b = []
d = []
c = 0
print("for random_state = ",a)
k=0.1
while(k<=0.95): 
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=1-k, random_state=a)
    print("train data percentage in total dataset : ", round(k,2))
    gnb = GaussianNB(priors=None)
    # gnb = GaussianNB(priors=[0.1, 0.5, 0.05, 0.05, 0.05, 0.05, 0.05, 0.05, 0.05, 0.05])
    fit = gnb.fit(X_train, y_train)
    predicted = fit.predict(X_test)
    print("accuracy = ", round(accuracy_score(y_test, predicted),4)) 
    b.append(round(accuracy_score(y_test, predicted),4))
    d.append(k)
    k += 0.05
    c += 1
pl.figure(figsize=(15,8))
pl.plot(d,b,'x-',label = 'Xsaved')
pl.xlabel('Train Percentage')
pl.ylabel('Test Data Accuracy')
pl.show()

Question 3

Please explain how the Gaussian Naive Bayesian model. How does Gaussian Naive Bayes algorithm work in the digits dataset? Assume that you are explaining it to a close friend of yours who has no background in data science but she is highly willing to learn it. Please do not forget to refer to the features, independence assumption, and labels.

Answer In Digits dataset, digits picture divide 64 small pictures and all 64 small pictures have own coler code between 0 and 15. All 64 small pictures coler codes are our features. Also we have number which is writed in the digits pictures. They are our labels. We divide our data two parts. one of them training(we build our model from training dateaset), second of them test(we test our model from test dataset and decice how good our model predict number on the picture.). In trainin dataset when we build our model we use both features and labels. And decide which features coler code takes which number. In gaussian Naive Bayes we calculate features probability for each number. And based on them we use test dataset features and predict their numbers. After that we compare predictions from test dataset and labels from test dataset. And find our model accuracy.

Source https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2017/09/naive-bayes-explained/

Please run the SVC (linear) code for iris dataset (that we worked during the class). Please perform the same algorithm for 4 different C values that you will decide. Then you should plot the outputs in the 2 x 2 plots (you need to get rid of the plots for label propagation but instead use SVC).

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn import datasets
from sklearn import svm
from sklearn.semi_supervised import label_propagation

rng = np.random.RandomState(0)
iris = datasets.load_iris()
X = iris.data[:, :2]
y = iris.target
# step size in the mesh
h = .02

# we create an instance of SVM and fit out data. We do not scale our
# data since we want to plot the support vectors

linear_svc_model_C_1 = (svm.SVC(kernel='linear',C = 1).fit(X, y), y)
linear_svc_model_C_10 = (svm.SVC(kernel='linear',C = 500).fit(X, y), y)
linear_svc_model_C_30 = (svm.SVC(kernel='linear',C = 5000).fit(X, y), y)
linear_svc_model_C_50 = (svm.SVC(kernel='linear',C = 50000).fit(X, y), y)

# create a mesh to plot in
x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h),
                     np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))
plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
# title for the plots
titles = ['SVC with linear kernel C=1',
          'SVC with linear kernel C=500',
          'SVC with linear kernel C=5000',
          'SVC with linear kernel C=50000']

color_map = {-1: (1, 1, 1), 0: (0, 0, .9), 1: (1, 0, 0), 2: (.8, .6, 0)}

for i, (clf, y_train) in enumerate((linear_svc_model_C_1, linear_svc_model_C_10, linear_svc_model_C_30, linear_svc_model_C_50)):
    # Plot the decision boundary. For that, we will assign a color to each
    # point in the mesh [x_min, x_max]x[y_min, y_max].
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i + 1)
    Z = clf.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    # Put the result into a color plot
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)
    
    plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, cmap=plt.cm.Paired)
    plt.axis('off')
    # Plot also the training points
    colors = [color_map[y] for y in y_train]
    plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=colors, edgecolors='black')
    plt.title(titles[i])


plt.suptitle("Unlabeled points are colored white", y=1)
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn import datasets
from sklearn import svm
from sklearn.semi_supervised import label_propagation

rng = np.random.RandomState(0)
iris = datasets.load_iris()
X = iris.data[:, :2]
y = iris.target
# step size in the mesh
h = .02

# we create an instance of SVM and fit out data. We do not scale our
# data since we want to plot the support vectors

rbf_svc_model_C_1 = (svm.SVC(kernel='rbf',C = 1).fit(X, y), y)
rbf_svc_model_C_10 = (svm.SVC(kernel='rbf',C = 500).fit(X, y), y)
rbf_svc_model_C_30 = (svm.SVC(kernel='rbf',C = 5000).fit(X, y), y)
rbf_svc_model_C_50 = (svm.SVC(kernel='rbf',C = 50000).fit(X, y), y)

# create a mesh to plot in
x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h),
                     np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))
plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
# title for the plots
titles = ['SVC with rbf kernel C=1',
          'SVC with rbf kernel C=500',
          'SVC with rbf kernel C=5000',
          'SVC with rbf kernel C=50000']

color_map = {-1: (1, 1, 1), 0: (0, 0, .9), 1: (1, 0, 0), 2: (.8, .6, 0)}

for i, (clf, y_train) in enumerate((rbf_svc_model_C_1, rbf_svc_model_C_10, rbf_svc_model_C_30, rbf_svc_model_C_50)):
    # Plot the decision boundary. For that, we will assign a color to each
    # point in the mesh [x_min, x_max]x[y_min, y_max].
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i + 1)
    Z = clf.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    # Put the result into a color plot
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)
    
    plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, cmap=plt.cm.Paired)
    plt.axis('off')
    # Plot also the training points
    colors = [color_map[y] for y in y_train]
    plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=colors, edgecolors='black')
    plt.title(titles[i])


plt.suptitle("Unlabeled points are colored white", y=1)
plt.show()

y = iris.target
# step size in the mesh
h = .02
# we create an instance of SVM and fit out data. We do not scale our
# data since we want to plot the support vectors

svc_model_linear = (svm.SVC(kernel='linear',C = 10, gamma = 2).fit(X, y), y)
svc_model_rbf = (svm.SVC(kernel='rbf',C = 10, gamma = 2).fit(X, y), y)
svc_model_poly = (svm.SVC(kernel='poly',C = 10, gamma = 2).fit(X, y), y)
svc_model_sigmoid = (svm.SVC(kernel='sigmoid',C = 10, gamma = 2).fit(X, y), y)

# create a mesh to plot in
x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h),
                     np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))
plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
# title for the plots
titles = ['SVC with linear kernel linear',
          'SVC with linear kernel rbf',
          'SVC with linear kernel poly',
          'SVC with linear kernel sigmoid']

color_map = {-1: (1, 1, 1), 0: (0, 0, .9), 1: (1, 0, 0), 2: (.8, .6, 0)}

for i, (clf, y_train) in enumerate((svc_model_linear, svc_model_rbf, svc_model_poly, svc_model_sigmoid)):
    # Plot the decision boundary. For that, we will assign a color to each
    # point in the mesh [x_min, x_max]x[y_min, y_max].
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i + 1)
    Z = clf.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    # Put the result into a color plot
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)
    
    plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, cmap=plt.cm.Paired)
    plt.axis('off')
    # Plot also the training points
    colors = [color_map[y] for y in y_train]
    plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=colors, edgecolors='black')
    plt.title(titles[i])


plt.suptitle("Unlabeled points are colored white", y=1)
plt.show()

Importance of C for Linear SVC

In [59]:
C = []
accuracy = []

i = 1  

while(i <= 1000):
    clf = SVC(kernel='linear',C = i, gamma = 2)
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train) 
    C.append(i)
    accuracy.append(clf.score(X_test, y_test, sample_weight=None))
    i += 1
pl.figure(figsize=(15,8))
pl.plot(C,accuracy,'x-',label = 'Xsaved')
pl.xlabel('C Value')
pl.ylabel('Accuracy')
pl.show()
  • For linear SVC: C value does not effect accuracy so much.

Question 6.

Please explain the need for semi-supervised learning methods. Please try to find a concrete example and discuss it. (At most 100 words).

Answer before search

  • If we have learn from data which does not have 100% labeled data. It is semi supervised learning.

Answer after search

  • In unsupervising learning data classifying based on similar features. We can choose number of clusters we want to divide. In semi supervising learning , we have some labeled data and we cluster our data to based on our distinnct label numbers and we classify them based on the similarities of labeled data. After than we build our models based on labeled and unlabeled data.

Question 7.

Please provide two concrete examples: one of them is more suitable for applying Naive Bayes algorithm and the other for Support Vector Machine algorithm. Provide a very rough comparison accordingly.

Naive Bayes Strengths and Weaknesses

  • Easy to implement
  • Simple
  • For example in text mining it does not classify based on words order.
  • Its main disadvantage is that it cant learn interactions between features. SVM Strengths and Weaknesses
  • They work really well in complicated domains where there is a clear margin of seperation.
  • They do not perform so well in very large data sets because the trainin time happens to be cubic in the size of the data set.
  • They also do not work well with lots and lots of noise.
  • When the class are very overlapping you have to count independent evidence. Naive Bayes Classifier would be better Example
  • https://www.kdnuggets.com/2017/03/email-spam-filtering-an-implementation-with-python-and-scikit-learn.html
  • In example for small spam dateset Naive Bayes is better to use, It gives same accuracy and it is basic and easy to implement.
  • But in example in the big spam dataset SVM gives better accuracy.
